definition.value: A tricyclic sesquiterpene with formula C15H26O, that is isolated from Streptomyces violaceusniger, S. malaysiensis and Leptographium lundbergii.
A spirocyclic diterpene with formula C20H32 which is produced by a diterpene cyclase gene expressed in an engineered Streptomyces host.
A nucleotide-sugar oxoanion arising from deprotonation of the free diphosphate OH groups of CDP-D-ribulose. Major microspecies at pH 7.3.
A nucleotide-sugar oxoanion arising from deprotonation of the free diphosphate OH groups of CDP-D-ribose. Major microspecies at pH 7.3.
A prostaglandin E derivative that is prostaglandin E1 in which one of the methyl hydrogens at position 20 has been replaced by a hydroxy group.
A tricyclic diterpene with formula C20H32 which is produced by a diterpene cyclase gene expressed in an engineered Streptomyces host.
A prostaglandin A derivative that is prostaglandin A1 in which one of the methyl hydrogens at position 20 has been replaced by a hydroxy group.
A tricyclic sesquiterpene with formula C15H24 which is biosynthesised from farnesyl diphosphate by a diterpene cyclase enzyme from Dictyostelium discoideum.
A bicyclic sesquiterpene with formula C15H24 which is biosynthesised from farnesyl diphosphate by a diterpene cyclase enzyme from Dictyostelium discoideum.
A steroidal acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 3-oxochenodeoxycholic acid.

A member of the cadinene family of sesquiterpenes having a 4,7-dimethyl-1-(propan-2-yl)-1,2,4a,5,6,8a-hexahydronaphthalene skeleton with 1S,4aR,8aS-stereochemistry. It is isolated from the essential oils of several plant species.
A choloyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 3-oxocholic acid.
A tricyclic sesquiterpenoid with formula C15H26O which is biosynthesised from farnesyl diphosphate by a sesquiterpene cyclase enzyme from Kitasatospora setae.
A tricyclic sesquiterpenoid with formula C15H26O which is biosynthesised from farnesyl diphosphate by a sesquiterpene cyclase enzyme from Kitasatospora setae.
A choloyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 3-oxodeoxycholic acid.
A choloyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 3-oxocholan-24-oic acid.
An L-alpha-amino acid residue derived from N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->4)-alpha-D-mannosyl-L-threonine.
An N-acyl-L-alpha-amino acid obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of propanoic acid with the amino group of L-methionine.
A dihydroxyicosatetraenoate that is the conjugate base of (5S,6R)-dihydroxy-(7E,9E,11Z,14Z)-icosatetraenoic acid arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid function; major species at pH 7.3.
A bis(hydroperoxy)icosatetraenoate that is the conjugate base of (5S,15S)-dihydroperoxy-(6E,8Z,11Z,13E)-icosatetraenoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
An icosanoid anion arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid function of any dihydroperoxyicosatetraenoic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A short-chain fatty acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of pivalic acid.
An hydroperoxy(hydroxy)icosatetraenoate that is the conjugate base of (5S)-hydroxy-(15S)-hydroperoxy-(6E,8Z,11Z,13E)-icosatetraenoic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
An hydroperoxy(hydroxy)icosatetraenoate that is the conjugate base of (5S,6R)-dihydroxy-(15S)-hydroperoxy-(7E,9E,11Z,13E)-icosatetraenoic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
An icosanoid anion that is any icosatetraenoate bearing hydroxy and hydroperoxy substituents. An oxidation product of icosatetraenoic acid metabolism.

A steroid acid anion, that is the conjugate base of pyridinestrone-3-carboxylic acid. An abiotic metabolite in the 4,5-seco pathway of aerobic estrogen degradation by the bacterium Sphingomonas sp. strain KC8.
An N-acyl-L-alpha-amino acid resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of any fatty acid with the amino group of any L-amino acid.
A glycoside consisting of D-glyceric acid having a 6-O-octanoyl-alpha-D-glucosyl-(1->6)-alpha-D-glucosyl residue attached at position 2 via a glycosidic linkage.
A glycoside consisting of D-glyceric acid having an alpha-D-glucosyl-(1->6)-alpha-D-glucosyl residue attached at position 2 via a glycosidic linkage.
A dihydroxyicosatetraenoate  that is the conjugate base of (5S,6S)-dihydroxy-(7E,9E,11Z,14Z)-icosatetraenoic acid arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid function; major species at pH 7.3.

An epoxide fluorescent probe for use in in vivo visualization of hydrogen sulfide. The probe employs a fluorescein as a fluorophore, and is equipped with an operating epoxide unit. FEPO functions via epoxide ring opening via nucleophilic attack by H2S.

An organic heterotricyclic compound that is 9H-imidazo[1,2-a]benzimidazole which is substituted at positions 2, 3, and 9 by phenyl, 2,3-dimethoxycinnamoyl, and methyl groups, respectively. It is a potent activator of osteoblast differentiation.

A member of the classs of octahydronaphthalenes and a sesquiterpene that is 1,2,3,4,4a,5,6,7-octahydronaphthalene which is substituted by an isopropenyl group at position 3 and by methyl groups at positions 4a and 5 (the 3S,4aS,5R- diastereoisomer).
A sesquiterpene that is 1,2,3,3a,4,5,6,8a-octahydroazulene carrying methyl, methylidene and isopropyl substituents at positions 1, 4 and 7 respectively.
A sesquiterpenoid obtained formally from (-)-germacrene A by hydroxylation at position 6 and hydrogenation across the C(11)-C(12) double bond.
A tricyclic diterpene with formula C20H32 which is produced by a diterpene cyclase gene expressed in roots of Arabidopsis.
An EC 2.5.1.* (non-methyl-alkyl or aryl transferase) inhibitor  that interferes with the action of cystathionine gamma-synthase (EC 2.5.1.48).
An 11-HETE(1-) that is the conjugate base of 11(S)-HETE, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
An enal obtained by formal dehydrogenation across positions 2 and 3 of any n-alkanal
